rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description:
A chemical compound is a molecular substance consisting of multiple atoms which are bonded together by a chemical reaction. This type can be used for compounds made of the same element (e.g. allotropes) or multiple different elements. Compounds are different from chemical mixtures because mixtures can be mixed and separated physically, without a reaction.
Things that are chemical compounds:
## Compounds that only contain one element (e.g. Dioxygen).
## Compounds that are used for medical treatments (e.g. Aspirin).
## Compounds that are drugs (e.g. Cocaine).
## Compounds that are hormones (e.g. Seratonin).
## Vitamins (e.g. Riboflavin aka Vitamin B2).
## Polymers (e.g. Polyglycolide, Amylose).
Things that are NOT chemical compounds:
## Individual elements (e.g. Neon). In this case, use mso:chemistry.chemical_element.
## Chemical mixtures and alloys (e.g. Bitumen, Smoke, and Brass).
## Isotopes (e.g. Hydrogen 1, Plutonium 241). In this case, use mso:chemistry.isotope.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Chemical Compound
